Inflation in Europe jumps because of food
The accelerating inflation measured in the euro area is mainly due to the constant rise in food prices.
November's price growth in 13 euro area countries was higher than expected, after 2.6 percent in October, annual inflation of 3.1 percent was recorded, the Luxembourg statistical office of the Union reported.
The official forecast was only 3%, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the U.S., British and Canadian Emission Banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the basic interest rate, with the decline, along with rising raw material prices and falling unemployment, leading to an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below 2%, but close to them.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in an absurd situation: it has to “betray” inflation so that it doesn’t have to do anything about it later.
In Germany, November inflation stands at 3.3 percent, a 15-year record; in Spain, it has risen from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent.
Inflation in the euro area has erupted due to sharply rising food and energy prices.
Wheat prices rose by 88 percent and soybean prices reached their highest level since 1973.
Similarly, in 2007 it was necessary to pay significantly more for edible oil and dairy products.
The price of oil in the world markets rose by 52 percent this year, and last month it already cost one barrel of black gold almost $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will jump from 2.1 percent in 2008 to 2.5 percent this year, but it will already fall to 1.9 percent in 2009.
According to analysts, the level of 12-month inflation in the next 3-4 months will continue to be approximately 3%, but its average annual rate will be 2.1%.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice in 2008.
