In many places, they save on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand cases of infection have been registered in hospitals, mainly due to improper use of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, overcrowding of beds, overcrowding of the staff to stop the disease do not help, says the head of the National Epidemiological Center.
In many places, they are also saved on disinfectants.
Recently, MRSA infection was diagnosed at the trauma department of St. John's Hospital.
Antibiotic-resistant bacteria were found in a man who was hospitalized after a serious car accident.
The patient was isolated.
A similar infection occurred at the same site at the beginning of the year.
The patient injured in a serious car accident was released home, but not long after he had to return with MRSA infection and because of the bacteria in his body, one important operation could not be performed.
Until December 10, 1,094 hospital infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens had been reported to the National System of Nessocomialis Surveillance, said Karolina Böröczov<0xC3><0xA1>, Prime Minister of the National Epidemiological Center.
This means that so many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have been registered in hospitals with certainty, the rest are unknown.
Nearly two-thirds (683) of infections were caused by MRSA, or methicillin-oxacillin-resistant golden staphylococcus.
The bacterium Staphylococcus aureus (SA) is carried by a third of people in the nose without causing disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. cervical inflammation, tonsillitis, skin infection, early infection) respond well to antibiotics and can be well treated.
However, if antibiotics are given excessively or inappropriately, a bacterium that responds well to antibiotics will develop a bacterium that is very resistant to antibiotics and that spreads rapidly in inadequate hospital conditions.
Especially in the case of temporary or permanent malfunction of the immune system in patients with a weakened organism, low body weight or in patients of years can cause serious hospital infections, such as early infection or blood poisoning - sepsis.
According to the chief physician of St. John's Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, similar infections in hospitals belong to daily practice.
"Infection should not be confused with an epidemic, MRSA is not just there," said Tibor Nyulasi, "where the presence of the causative agent of the disease is not studied."
Resistant to antibiotics
“We are isolating these patients, treating them with rubber gloves and masks, and we have the antibiotics we need to treat them,” Nyulasi said.
Patients admitted to the hospital are first examined to see if MRSA is present in their body, but infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling is not in fashion
The vast majority of hospital-acquired MRSA infections could be prevented, but current conditions in home hospitals are not conducive to preventing the onset and spread of multidrug-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröczov<0xC3><0xA1>.
Since this infection occurs symptomatically in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should monitor patients admitted and immediately isolate MRSA carriers.
However, the collection of microbiological samples in Hungarian hospitals is not in fashion.
The National Health Insurance Fund does not fund these investigations.
Most cases are detected if the patient suffers from a detectable MRSA infection, the head of the epidemiological center said.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the appropriate treatment of antibiotics in the field of human medicine, and there are also domestic guidelines for the treatment of individual infections, disease reports.
There is a need to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, or microbiological examinations should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, although hospitals do not comply in all cases.
The collection of microbiological samples is even rarer in basic and outpatient treatment of patients, said Karolina Böröczov<0xC3><0xA1>.
Saves on disinfectants
According to scientific evidence, MRSA is most often spread among patients through medical personnel.
Therefore, hand washing and the use of gloves and masks play a very important role, but there are also serious shortcomings in hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection and touch, but it is not always possible to isolate infected patients in the conditions of home hospitals.
On the contrary, the rooms are often crowded, the beds are often very close to each other, although from an epidemiological point of view, patients should be at least 1.5 meters apart.
Unfortunately, as Karolina Böröczov<0xC3><0xA1> noted, we can also find that in hospitals that are in an unfavorable material situation, there are few disinfectants, nurses and many patients, which increases the chances of infections.
According to Karolina Böröczov<0xC3><0xA1>, where the necessary protective measures are observed, similar infections are demonstrably less common or the further spread of the causative agent of the disease can be stopped.
Government Program Against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA is a huge expense for health insurance companies, which is why it is being fought everywhere.
For example, in England, the government has drafted a program to prevent MRSA or reduce its occurrence.
The program appears to be successful, according to published data, MRSA infections are showing a declining trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) ranks the prevention of multi-resistant disease agents (including MRSA) and hospital infections caused by these agents as its priorities.
