In addition, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, according to the research institute, due to the great attention of domestic and foreign media, "significantly distorted the image of Hungary abroad, especially in terms of belief in the stability of the country and its democratic development".
As part of the reorganization of Hungarian radical and ultra-right groups, which have gained increasing publicity and vehemence since the autumn of 2006, several organisations have been formed in Hungary since the summer of 2007, which call themselves "national defence associations".
"The common feature of these groups is that they define themselves as civic associations, while openly proclaiming - even armed - the readiness of their members to perform defensive tasks (in the case of natural disasters, invading the homeland, disturbing the order), in addition to pointing to the inability of the police, the army, or the state," he added.
He further notes: all this is happening in a way that seeks to wrap all sorts of political efforts built on society’s resistance to politics and parties in civilian clothes.
Therefore, the emphasis on civility and the form of the association in the case of these groups not only serves to avoid the legal pitfalls of judicial registration, but is also a political strategy.
According to the analysis, the activity of the Hungarian Guard is also a risk-enhancing factor from the point of view of neighbourly relations.
“In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been pointed out in several neighbouring countries as a potential source of danger, and ultranationalist political leaders of some neighbouring countries want to apologise for their own anti-Hungarian policies by appealing to the creation of the Hungarian Guard.
All this can affect the political stability of the region," he added.
According to the research institute, the emergence of the Hungarian Guard in Central and Eastern Europe is not a unique phenomenon, so political risks for the region as a whole have increased.
According to him, the activity of the Hungarian Guard is similar, for example, to the activity of the Bulgarian National Guard, whose creation was announced in August 2007 by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
Against the backdrop of the formation of the Bulgarian Guard, there are mass Romani riots that broke out in one of Sofia’s districts (Krasna Poljana).
The BNU used this to establish a guard, saying that the organization's goal was "national defense".
In the past 17 years, she said, there has been "gypsy terror" in Bulgaria, but the state has remained idle and indifferent.
He adds that the initiative sparked a turbulent debate among the Bulgarian public.
The increase in the risk of ethnic clashes signals the announcement by some Bulgarian Roma organizations that they will create their own guards as a sign of resistance.
Since the current activity of the Hungarian Guard shows similarities with the activity of the Bulgarian National Guard, it is possible that the Hungarian Roma will react to the threat in a similar way, by establishing their own militia, we can read in the risk warning prepared by the Political Capital Institute.
Asked by the press office, Attila Juh<0xC3><0xA1>sz, Research Director of the Political Capital Institute, said that risk analysis is one of the activities of the research institute.
As he said, risk analysis is issued every year and if they find anything that could affect the change in risk, they inform public opinion, as in this case by issuing a risk warning.
Holidays are not free everywhere
In Hungary, the days off are determined precisely by law and it has already become a common practice that working days are moved around the holidays, which we expect less times in the next year.
In the European Union and America, holidays are not uniform.
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between national and state holidays and days of rest.
Days of rest are usually associated with church holidays or important historical events.
Here we also celebrate the New Year: the last day of the old and the first day of the new year is a work holiday - on the New Year, so that people can rest after New Year's Eve.
During the year, we have 11 free holidays.
The national holiday is March 15, celebrating the Revolution of 1848, and October 23, commemorating the Revolution of 1956.
On August 20th we celebrate the founding of the state, on May 1st work, on November 1st and 2nd we remember the deceased relatives and friends.
In addition, the two-day holidays are Easter, Pentecost and Christmas.
Since our national, national, or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, it has become a practice to move the working day if we only work one day before or after a holiday.
The price for extended weekends, however, is that the previous Saturdays we stayed in the workplace and at school.
The day that immediately precedes or follows the holiday, when we work, has been regulated by the Minister of Labour in a special decree for many years.
The legislation applies equally to all employers and their employees, to public employees and to persons in the public service.
However, it does not apply to companies and institutions that are in operation without interruption or operate even on days of rest.
This year there will be a change of working conditions only around the holidays at the end of the year: from December 24, life in the country will almost stop, because according to the experience so far, most people will "work" in advance between Christmas and New Year's Eve or use the saved vacation in this way.
Next year, several of our holidays fall in the middle, or at the end of the week, so there will be fewer shifts of the working day than this year.
For the first time, the calendar changes around the holiday of work, so that workers can stay at home for four days of taste.
Saturday the 26th of April will be a working day, so that Friday the 2nd of May can be a rest day.
Another transfer is related to the holiday of October 23: on Saturday, October 18, work will be done instead of Friday, October 24.
However, the end of the year next year will be able to take place entirely in the sign of holidays, because from December 24 they will have almost non-stop holidays everywhere, despite the fact that New Year's Eve falls on Wednesday.
6 Disturbing Things You Can Do to Annoy Your Colleagues
Emails that we forget to send, voice messages that we never get, innocent lies that we almost never notice: all of this "spreads up" the weekdays in the workplace.
The question is, do you get used to these little inconveniences, or put on gloves, and deliberately avoid unclear situations that can make others angry.
Tips.
"I'm sorry, I forgot to tell you they were looking for you from the marketing department," a colleague will tell you.
That you missed the meeting for that?
At best, he regrets it and will try to fix it, or call the marketing department and say that he forgot to pass the message (this is a less common solution).
Most often, the matter is resolved with one apology.
Before there is any embarrassing apology, it is good to think about what you can do to prepare your colleagues for unpleasant moments, and consciously try to prevent it.
Do you borrow something that is not yours?
There’s nothing more annoying than stretching out for a piece of paper, office supplies, or for your phone, and they’re not there.
Do you remember putting a stapler on your desk yesterday, but it's gone by morning?
Or did you find a pen on the desk of one of your colleagues that you thought was lost?
Do not take anything from your colleagues without permission, otherwise they will rightly be angry at you for messing with their things.
Do not take envelopes or adhesive paper out of the office, as it can be uncomfortable when you run out of it prematurely, and you will need it immediately.
Rumors about the private life of colleagues?
There is no good way to stop the rumors from spreading.
Who, who, what was he doing?
Where and why?
Don’t tell everyone your news (suppositions) about the private life of colleagues!
When one of them shares his innermost secrets with you, do not abuse his trust!
Lock in what you have heard, and in his absence do not discuss it with your colleagues, even when others know about his things.
Are you claiming your absence for no reason?
If you call the office and report your absence, citing a severe headache, because you are not well, or you say that you would rather rest today, think about the fact that your work, urgent tasks and work with a certain deadline will have to be done for you by someone else.
Take care of your colleagues!
If you know in advance that you won’t go to work the next day, or that something might happen that will make you have to stay at home, report it so that your colleagues and supervisors aren’t confronted with your absence until the next day.
Popping, giggling, telephone
Have you been immersed in a job that will rudely rip you out of the whining of your colleagues?
Inadvertently, have you witnessed a telephone conversation that would be better not to hear at all?
Do not disturb your co-workers by humming, chanting, loud talking (them overhead), or kicking, constantly swearing, loud dissatisfaction.
All this can be disruptive even when they are not involved in a project (writing, planning, organization).
Do you blame others for their mistakes?
If something is not on time or you have forgotten to send an important letter or message, do not blame the other for your forgetfulness!
Do not refer to the chaos in the office and the noisy colleagues!
Recognize if you made a mistake and someone paid for it, and repair the damage!
Ask how you can put things in order, correct negligence!
Do you feel at home in your office?
Sweatshirts and slippers: comfortable clothes for home, but not suitable for the office!
Don’t wear casual clothes, even if your profession allows it!
Don’t be careless, honor your colleagues and yourself by coming to the office in a regular dress – and if your profession requires it, nice and elegantly!
