Banks want to solve the crisis
The US Federal Reserve Bank, the European Central Bank and the central banks of Britain, Switzerland and Canada have decided to jointly fight the crisis in the financial markets.
More than $100 billion will go to the currency markets through auctions.
In these auctions, banks auction interest rates at which they are willing to borrow money.
For example, the U.S. Federal Reserve will auction $40 billion and then make another $24 billion available to the European and Swiss central banks.
It is the first time since the September 11 attacks that national central banks have agreed on such a coordinated procedure to prevent or reduce the consequences of the financial crisis.
“This step is to address the economy’s biggest challenge, the growing shortage of free capital that banks could lend,” Bernard Baumohl, of the Economic Outlook Group, said in a statement.
“Coordinated central bank action has reduced the likelihood of a recession in the United States from 65 percent to 50 percent,” Baumohl said in a statement.
Banks have already lost $60 billion due to unpaid loans, mainly in the United States.
Analysts expect further billions of dollars in losses.
“Central banks must be really worried about what else can happen when they decide to do this,” said ABN’s chief economist, Amro Kieran Davies.
"It looks like the situation is really bad," he added.
Central banks are concerned that if banks themselves have difficult access to loans, they will also lend to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and send the U.S. economy into recession, with potential impacts on global economic growth.
The central banks decided to do so after failing to lower the so-called LIBOR rate, the London interbank rate used to lend money in the interbank market.
This meant that banks were still worried about lending each other money, despite the fact that the central banks of the US, Canada and the UK lowered their interest rates several times in the fall.
"It will have the same effect as the next fall in interest rates," Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
Some analysts do not believe that the move by central banks will contribute to the resolution of the crisis, because it does not solve the underlying problem, and this is the collapse of the real estate market in the United States.
