Loaded memory
After more than sixty years in a confidential regime, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which depict the fate of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are open to the public.
The 47 million archival documents stored for 27 km in Bad Arolsen (Hesse) were, until that time, accessible only for "humanitarian" purposes, that is, individually and specifically, at the request of the former victim or his authorized persons.
Eleven of the countries responsible for managing archives - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May to open them to scientists and historians.
As the process of ratification of this agreement by all states is over, the opening took effect yesterday.
Sensitive information
Historians’ free access to Bad Arolsen will allow them to examine “particularly the movements of prisoners, the camp population, and the health of forced laborers,” explains Reto Meistern, director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (Comité international de la Croix-rouge, CICR).
Until recently, several states, including Germany, were opposed to making these nominal documents available to the public, due to the sensitive nature of some information.
What are the presumed homosexuality or mental disability of some victims of deportation?
The registers of concentration camps or warrants compiled by the Gestapo were collected after the war for the practical purpose of finding deported or forced labor subjected to civilians, to bring them proof of their internment in order to open the way for their compensation.
Even today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen deal with tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, for part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen represents only a limited benefit.
“Nothing fundamentally new can be expected from these documents,” said Prof. Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for the Study of Antisemitism at the Technische Universität Berlin in 2006.
