Congress Approves MiFID Transposition Effective November 1
In parallel with the parliamentary negotiations that were concluded today with a congressional vote on the amendments incorporated by the Senate into the bill, the government has submitted to a public hearing a regulation that is developing the new law, with the aim of both coming into force before the end of the year.
Members and senators’ efforts to negotiate and agree on the best standard to guarantee investor protection and detailed regulation of the activities of the entities necessary for the efficient functioning of the markets were similarly highlighted by the representatives of the various parties.
The MiFID Directive, which regulates the Securities Trading Act, provides for the modernisation of financial markets while strengthening investor protection, improves the supervisory powers of the State Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promotes cooperation between the various supervisory authorities of the European Union.
This new regulation will enable the provision of financial advisory services to both specialised firms and natural or legal persons, and will create a new type of financial services firm (ESIS), financial advisory company (AFI) that joins securities companies, securities brokerage firms and portfolio management companies.
In addition, the number of systems for the execution of transactions with financial instruments is being expanded to include multilateral trading systems and order internalisation systems that will compete with current stockbrokers.
The law also obliges firms providing investment services to disseminate information on key aspects of their business profile, exposure to risk and ways of dealing with risk on the market, and requires the CNMV to keep a record of all operations carried out to simplify supervision.
During the debate in the Congressional Trade Commission, several adjustments were included, among which it stands out that the securitized receivables were considered a "complex" financial instrument due to the high risk to the investor, which was proven by what happened in the US with high-risk mortgage debts (subprime).
In addition, the transposition of the directive was used to legally define the functions that bachelors in economics and business management can hold 30 years after the Royal Decree was adopted in 1977, which sets out professional functions reserved for economists.
At the same time, the Senate included the creation of new professions in the financial sector, such as an intermediary that will work externally, will not require permission from CNMV and will be able to provide product trading and client acquisition services for various investment firms at the same time.
