Concerns over new gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
There is a dispute between Russia and Ukraine over the price of natural gas, which increases the risk that the Russian supply of this fuel to Western Europe may be affected.
Most of the Russian fuel exported to the European Union (EU) is piped through Ukraine, and any dispute between the two countries is closely monitored.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow raises gas prices to Ukraine, Russia will be charged higher transit fees.
The previous dispute between the two countries reduced supplies to EU countries last year.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes as the Ukrainian government and Russia’s state-owned gas monopoly, Gazprom, are trying to agree on how much Ukraine will have to pay for Russian gas in 2008.
Gazprom says it will have to charge Ukraine more because it has agreed to pay up to 50% more for the gas it receives from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say this could mean that Ukraine will have to pay 40% more for its supplies from Gazprom.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states during the negotiations," Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinakh told Reuters.
"The changes in gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the amount of transit fees (to Western Europe) through Ukraine."
The last major dispute between Moscow and Kiev caused a reduction in supplies from Gazprom to Ukraine in January 2006.
This caused a massive drop in exports to Western Europe, which sharply increased prices.
Russian gas accounts for one-quarter of the EU’s gas supply.
Russia has the largest gas reserves in the world, but much of them remain under-exploited.
As a result, Gazprom is replenishing its own gas supplies from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet Central Asian republics.
The NHS “must check foreign employees”
The auditor said the Scottish chambers of the NHS must improve criminal records checks on non-European employees.
The recommendation from the president of the Supreme Audit Office, Robert Black, came after a foreign doctor operating in Scotland was linked to the June attacks on Glasgow Airport.
Mr. Black also fears that the Scottish NHS has no precise idea of the amount of foreign personnel it employs.
But his report stressed that the other key checks were in order on a sample of five health authorities.
The president of the Supreme Audit Office was immediately interested in staff recruited from countries outside the European Economic Area following the June attacks on Glasgow Airport.
Bilal Abdullah, a 28-year-old Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was detained at the airport after someone drove a Jeep into the door of the main terminal building.
He was one of three doctors who appeared at the Central Criminal Court using a video bridge accused of linking to attempted bombings in the UK.
The NHS Chambers are expected to check foreign personnel for qualifications, experience and authorization to work in the UK before their employment.
Although the Scottish Health Commissions use Disclosure Scotland to check criminal records, the agency has no authority to obtain such information outside the UK.
The report by the President of the Supreme Audit Office says, among other recommendations, that the commission should be guided by the Criminal Records Bureau directives, which help employers with checks in several countries.
"Although we found that some of the personnel records contained evidence of these checks, they are not carried out regularly," the report said.
Mr. Black said the Scottish NHS is largely in line with its own pre-employment screening policy, but added: “Our report draws attention to areas where the system could be improved to ensure that accurate information about the amount of foreign personnel is available.”
Dr Peter Terry, chairman of the BMA Scotland, said it was “very unlikely” that pre-employment checks would identify potential NHS employees who could commit a terrorist act in the future.
