None of this means that Mr. Brown is unavoidably heading towards his end.
In spite of this, governments can reach a tipping point where they find government difficult.
The people don't trust politicians and don't like them, but they usually put away their mistrust when a new party takes over.
When it seems clear that a prime minister probably won’t improve anything, and doesn’t even have to be in office for long, this push is gone: the state administration is becoming hollow, ministers are starting to brief, the press is looking for bad news, and the government is becoming unfocused and defensive.
In one direction, Mr Brown's position is particularly difficult, because, unlike other political leaders, he cannot take the position of a new broom.
As much as he wanted to distance himself from Tony Blair, he was his first officer.
