That would require the Labours, who are in a tight spot, to cooperate with the Conservatives, and perhaps even to relinquish their special financial relationship with the trade unions—the bitter pill for a devoted party member like Mr. Brown.
But he should face some simple facts.
Conservatives now have a decent lead in the polls; he has two years to win back voters; and the only way to win is unquestionable integrity and high competence.
