Does the Mortgage Crisis Affect the U.S. Credit Card Market?
When there is blood in the water, the spinal fins naturally begin to blink excitedly around.
As the U.S. real estate market slumps, predators have turned their attention to the credit card market there.
Analysts at Goldman Sachs say that credit card losses could reach $99 billion if other consumer loan options were contaminated by underprivileged mortgages.
The signs of tension are clear.
There is an increasing number of inability to repay (with more than 30 days of late payment) and debited accounts (accounts that the provider considers unenforceable).
HSBC announced last month that it had lost $1.4 billion in the U.S. consumer credit market - also due to insolvency credit card loans.
But it is too early to panic.
Unpaid bills and inability to pay are still few.
According to Moody’s, the 3.89 percent insolvency rate in the third quarter was almost a full percentage point below average.
The deteriorating rates can be partly explained by technical reasons.
The 2005 change in U.S. personal bankruptcy laws led to a sharp decline in the number of reported bankruptcies, which account for a large proportion of credit card losses; thus, the number of reports (and thus the number of write-offs) would rise regardless of whether the general conditions for borrowers have deteriorated.
The industry also shows a good maturity rate, which shows how much consumers pay off their debts monthly.
And confidence in the securities of secured credit cards is solid, despite the paralysis in other corners of structured finance.
Mr. Dennis Moroney of the TowerGroup research firm predicts that their emissions for 2007 will be 25% higher than last year.
Direct routes for the spread of infection between the crisis of subprime mortgages and the credit card market certainly exist: when real estate loans dry up, consumers are more likely to get in debt through credit cards.
Credit card issuers, however, look at the cash flow rather than the values of the guarantee items, so falling house prices do not necessarily mean a change in the credibility of borrowers.
They can even be beneficial for lenders.
Consumers’ motivation to pay off mortgages declines as the value of their assets falls below the value of the loan; as a result, card debt moves up the priority list for repayment.
Card issuers can also respond faster and more flexibly to more turbulent conditions than mortgage providers by changing interest rates or debt limits.
This should theoretically reduce the risks of a rapid change in the prices of guarantor items.
“It’s not going to happen that one beautiful morning we’re just going to rethink all of our loans,” said Gary Perlin, chief financial officer at Capital One.
Although the risk of an explosion in the style of inferior mortgages is low, the risk of gradual weakening is much more real.
If lower home prices and debt reduction push America into recession, the credit card industry will face a darker future.
Watch out for those back fins.
