The first buses full of Iraqi refugees from Syria began arriving in Baghdad yesterday to dump refugees who ran out of money or expired visas, and others who hoped the city would return to normal life.
Some even returned to fight the militants who had driven them out of their homes.
The Mansour bus station was full of refugees from Syria and Jordan who had returned by private transport before 800 people arrived from Damascus in an official government convoy of dozens of buses.
"I decided to go to Syria after many doctors were killed in Baghdad," said Sabah al-Kubaisi, a Sunni doctor.
