"They say the Mahdi army has stopped killing people," he said, referring to the Shia militia of militant cleric Muqtada al-Sadr, who temporarily ordered his people to stop fighting.
Qasim al-Atwani, an 38-year-old Shia teacher from the predominantly Sunni Amariah region, returned with his two children because he could no longer renew his Syrian visas and because the regime there did not allow Iraqis to work.
His Shia neighbors in Amariah called him saying that the local militia, with the support of the U.S. military, had helped push al-Qaeda out of its positions in the west of the capital, and urged him to return.
One of the newcomers from Jordan is the leader of a Sunni and Shia tribe that was expelled from his home in Sleikh in northern Baghdad by a grenade attack after he urged his fellow citizens to rise up against al-Qaeda.
He came back to fight.
“On the day before yesterday, a few friends called me and told me that they were launching an al-Qaeda militia in Sleikh and that they needed me and the support of my boys.
That's why I came back today," Sabaah Alu Obeidi, 62, said.
Many have spoken about the attraction of calm in the capital after the strengthening of the US military presence and the growth of local “groups of biased citizens” who, with arms in hand, side by side with the US military, defend their quarters.
