Venus is the Earth's infernal twin.
Despite its life-threatening atmosphere, Venus is more similar to Earth than previously thought. The European Venus Express spacecraft on Venus has recorded phenomena that occur on Earth in winter: lightning in the atmosphere and winds at the poles.
For nearly three decades, scientists have suspected that Venus is flashing.
Now the European probe Venus Express has brought evidence - captured electromagnetic waves on the edge of the atmosphere. On Venus, lightning flies from cloud to cloud at an altitude of about 56 kilometers, wrote in the scientific magazine Nature Christopher Russell from the University of California, Los Angeles.
According to the famous theory of the origin of primordial matter, life could have been created on Earth by lightning. Storms are said to have triggered reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the cornerstones of life.
It wasn’t like that on Venus: “If life ever existed there, it must have been a long time ago,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institute in Washington.
The atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than the Earth’s, and sometimes temperatures are around 500 °C.
"Out there, maybe, it's the Earth's hell twin, but it's the Earth's twin," Russell said.
Why Venus, which is so similar in size and mass to Earth, began to evolve in a completely different way, is a fundamental question of the Esa mission.
Since no spacecraft had been sent to study Venus since the early 1990s, the launch of Venus Express in November 2005 was a milestone in the exploration of the planet.
According to scientists, the latest results of research, which brought several articles of the journal Nature, did not only emphasize the uniqueness of Venus in the solar system.
"They also showed that our neighboring planet is more Earth-like than previously thought," Esa said.
In addition to the already known wind swirls at the North Pole, scientists have found a cloud swirl at the South Pole, which spins significantly faster.
This phenomenon is reminiscent of air currents in the Earth's northern hemisphere, writes a research team led by Guiseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second innermost planet in our solar system is almost the same mass as Earth, and with a diameter of 12,100 km is almost the same size.
This planet, known as Morning Star or Evening Star, will orbit the Sun in nearly 225 days.
However, it rotates much more slowly around its own axis. One day on Venus lasts 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus has a surface temperature of 460°C and a pressure of 92 bar, scientists believe that the two planets formed under very similar conditions.
Water had accumulated on both of them, but it remained on Earth in the oceans while it evaporated from Venus into space.
While carbon dioxide on Earth is bound in carbonates on Earth, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
