These aren't Warhol's boxes.
The one who combines the terms Sweden and wooden boxes does not think of Andy Warhol, but of Ikea.
Or is it?
Wooden boxes currently made in Sweden cast dark shadows on Warhol’s list of works.
Most of his list of the ninety-four "Brillo Boxes" of the Stockholm type are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" a few months ago expressed doubts about the authenticity of the international market as well as of Warhol's 1968 "Brillo Boxes", the internal research of the Moderna Museet Museum in Stockholm comes with a result that brought disappointment; six "Brillo Boxes", which in 1995 to the Museum of Moderna Museet were donated by his former director Hultus
Previous events are a tangled, confusing chain of artistic and curatorial events.
Warhol made his first Brillo boxes in New York in 1964, painting wooden boxes that were based on the red-and-white design of the paper boxes of Brillo soap powder.
An exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet in 1968 showed - with Warhol's consent - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard. These were not (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo factory.
It was not about works of art, but about their designs, mere exhibition pieces.
Warhol apparently also gave permission in 1968 to produce several wooden Brillo boxes in Sweden, but they are not on display in the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses at the time are now talking about fifteen boxes, which at that time rightfully entered the art and auction history as authorized originals - "Andy Warhol's Brillo Box" with the designation Type Stockholm.
Some of them were auctioned for more than $100,000.
The problem now lies in the fact that the legendary director of the museum, Pontus Hultén, later falsely claimed that in 1968 about a hundred crates were produced and exhibited in Sweden, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, 105 Hultén cases were produced in Malmö for the exhibition in St. Petersburg only in 1990.
By this time Warhol was three years after his death.
Lars Byström, the chief conservator of the Moderna Museet, explored, in addition to the six Brillo boxes owned by the museum, three Brillo boxes from the Swedish private collection, two of which were made in Sweden in 1968 and after their plywood plates were painted in base paint and trimmed, they were brushed on a brush.
On the contrary, it turned out from the structure of the 1990 copies that the paint was applied with a paint roll directly on the plywood board without previous primer - in addition, it is an acrylic and not an oil paint.
“These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from Warhol’s official Brillo Boxes list,” said Moderna Museet director Lars Nittve: “If the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York doesn’t come to other conclusions, Moderna Museet will have to classify six boxes from its exhibition collections as ‘buildings’.
As early as July, the Authentication Board announced that it would deal with these “major allegations” raised in the case of soap powder boxes.
